class_2_total = survival_by_class.iloc[1]['total_passengers']
class_3_total = survival_by_class.iloc[2]['total_passengers']

analysis_text = f"""Analysis of Passenger Class and Survival Rate on the Titanic:

CORRELATION:
There is a strong negative correlation between passenger class and survival rate (correlation coefficient: {correlation_coeff}). This means that as the class number increases (1st → 2nd → 3rd), the survival rate decreases significantly.

SURVIVAL RATES BY CLASS:
• 1st Class: {class_1_rate}% survival rate ({class_1_total} passengers)
• 2nd Class: {class_2_rate}% survival rate ({class_2_total} passengers)  
• 3rd Class: {class_3_rate}% survival rate ({class_3_total} passengers)

KEY INSIGHTS:
1. First-class passengers were nearly twice as likely to survive compared to third-class passengers
2. The survival rate drops dramatically from 1st class to 3rd class (a difference of {class_1_rate - class_3_rate} percentage points)
3. Socioeconomic status was a critical factor in survival, likely due to:
   - Better cabin locations (closer to lifeboats and exits)
   - Priority access during evacuation
   - Better knowledge of emergency procedures
   - Physical proximity to the ship's crew and safety equipment

